




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Strategic Pricing of Reproducible Consumer Products
AU  - Nascimento, Fernando
AU  - Vanhonacker, Wilfried R.
Y1  - 1988/08/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.34.8.921
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.34.8.921
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 921
EP  - 937
VL  - 34
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper investigates the strategic pricing of consumer durable products which can be acquired through either purchase or reproduction (e.g., computer software). As copy piracy results in an opportunity loss, its adverse effect on profits needs to be incorporated in strategic decisions such as pricing. Using a dual diffusion model which parsimoniously describes sales and copying, and employing control theory methodology, optimal price trajectories are derived for the period of monopoly. The results indicate that (a) in absence of any protection, skimming pricing strategies are generally optimal, and (b) copy protection is warranted only when sales diffuse much faster than copying and the protection technology does not significantly raise the marginal production cost.
AB  - This paper investigates the strategic pricing of consumer durable products which can be acquired through either purchase or reproduction (e.g., computer software). As copy piracy results in an opportunity loss, its adverse effect on profits needs to be incorporated in strategic decisions such as pricing. Using a dual diffusion model which parsimoniously describes sales and copying, and employing control theory methodology, optimal price trajectories are derived for the period of monopoly. The results indicate that (a) in absence of any protection, skimming pricing strategies are generally optimal, and (b) copy protection is warranted only when sales diffuse much faster than copying and the protection technology does not significantly raise the marginal production cost.
